⁠
Set against the backdrop of Central Park, the visuals lean into an NYC energy, with Jones fitting naturally into Louis Vuitton’s ongoing conversation between luxury and the street. Swipe for a closer look.

@julianklincewicz connection to @vans goes way beyond collaboration. Growing up in Southern California, Vans was tied to everything from skate culture to Warped Tour, and that nostalgia still shapes his work with Vans OTW today. His latest collections focus on reviving overlooked classics like the Style 31, using subtle updates in color, materials, and texture to capture the feeling of early 2000s San Diego.⁠
⁠
For Klincewicz, the worn-in look is really about memory and lived experience. Faded fabrics, scuffed shoes, and ripped laces tell personal stories in a way new products can’t, which is why his latest Vans styles feel less like fresh releases and more like old favorites pulled straight from someone’s closet.

@JacobAndCo. unveils the Godfather II, a $440,000 musical timepiece that brings cinema to the wrist.
Drawing inspiration from one of film’s most iconic sagas, the watch integrates two legendary compositions — The Godfather’s Waltz and The Godfather Love Theme — played through an intricate, built-in music box.
Encased in a sculpted Art Deco-inspired design, the piece combines horological artistry with cinematic storytelling. A flying tourbillon, dual power reserves, and a newly engineered movement elevate both its technical and aesthetic appeal, while the dial features a finely detailed portrait of Don Corleone alongside subtle references to the film’s legacy.
Limited to just 74 pieces, in tribute to the 1974 release of The Godfather Part II, the timepiece stands as a rare collector’s creation, where music, craftsmanship, and heritage converge.
