Forget Year of the Fire Horse. It’s the year of the jasmine. At the Met Gala earlier this week, Isha Ambani stepped out in a look that was an homage to India on so many levels. A key element of her ensemble? The string of jasmine she had pinned to her hair. But Ambani’s gajra probably didn’t leave the flower’s famously delicate floral scent in her wake since hers was carefully constructed from paper and metal buds in the studio of Brooklyn-based Sourabh Gupta(@sourabh_gupta_studio).
For many Indian designers, the fragile jasmine has become a medium through which they’re able to offer a more personal, nuanced take on fashion’s enduring obsession with flowers. While Dior(@dior) had his cyclamen and lily of the valley and Oscar de la Renta(@oscardelarenta) had his gardenias and chrysanthemums, we have bountiful bouquets of our own to pluck from, and this moment is for the mogra.
